y:block;}.css-j1vyw6 .e16qazw92{margin-top:0.25rem;}</style><figure class="css-j1vyw6 e12yhaj20"><img alt="在康涅狄格州米德尔敦卫斯理大学的毕业典礼结束时，学生们将帽子抛向空中。" fetchpriority="high" width="1280" height="720" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color:transparent" sizes="(min-width: 960px) 700px, 95vw" srcset="https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=360,quality=80,format=auto/media-assets/image/20230826_PDP506.jpg 360w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=384,quality=80,format=auto/media-assets/image/20230826_PDP506.jpg 384w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=480,quality=80,format=auto/media-assets/image/20230826_PDP506.jpg 480w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=600,quality=80,format=auto/media-assets/image/20230826_PDP506.jpg 600w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=834,quality=80,format=auto/media-assets/image/20230826_PDP506.jpg 834w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=960,quality=80,format=auto/media-assets/image/20230826_PDP506.jpg 960w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1096,quality=80,format=auto/media-assets/image/20230826_PDP506.jpg 1096w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1280,quality=80,format=auto/media-assets/image/20230826_PDP506.jpg 1280w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1424,quality=80,format=auto/media-assets/image/20230826_PDP506.jpg 1424w" src="https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1424,quality=80,format=auto/media-assets/image/20230826_PDP506.jpg" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></figure></section><p class="article__body-text"><small><span data-caps="initial">我</span>的大学</small>学位值得吗？当数百万准备申请大学的学生面临着这个问题。这是许多毕业生可能正在考虑的一个问题，因为他们必须再次开始偿还大学债务。美国在疫情期间暂停偿还学生债务的规定将于 9 月结束。</p><p class="article__body-text">在本周的播客中，主持人爱丽丝·富尔伍德、汤姆·李-德夫林和迈克·伯德探讨了大学是否仍然值得花时间和金钱。芝加哥布斯商学院的康斯坦丁·雅内利斯 (Constantine Yannelis) 解释了当多达 4500 万美国人再次面临学生债务偿还问题时，美国经济将受到怎样的影响。被前总统奥巴马任命为美国教育部部长的迈克尔·伊茨科维茨 (Michael Itzkowitz) 透露，学生在教育上的投资经常无法获得回报。时长：40分钟</p><p class="article__body-text"><iframe height="2